In book one of the series,

47
00:01:56,647 --> 00:01:58,230
"The Biggest Ideas in the Universe,"

48
00:01:58,230 --> 00:02:00,120
called "Space, Time and Motion,"

49
00:02:00,120 --> 00:02:02,490
you take on classical mechanics,

50
00:02:02,490 --> 00:02:06,510
general relativity by
taking on the main equation

51
00:02:06,510 --> 00:02:07,440
of general relativity

52
00:02:07,440 --> 00:02:10,260
and making it accessible,
easy to understand.

53
00:02:10,260 --> 00:02:13,410
So maybe at the high level,

54
00:02:13,410 --> 00:02:15,510
what is general relativity?

55
00:02:15,510 --> 00:02:18,810
What's a good way to start
to try to explain it?

56
00:02:18,810 --> 00:02:20,070
- Probably the best way to start to try

57
00:02:20,070 --> 00:02:22,140
to explain it is special relativity,

58
00:02:22,140 --> 00:02:24,183
which came first, 1905.

59
00:02:25,020 --> 00:02:27,690
It was the culmination of many decades

60
00:02:27,690 --> 00:02:28,890
of people putting things together.

61
00:02:28,890 --> 00:02:31,710
But it was Einstein in 1905.

62
00:02:31,710 --> 00:02:32,850
In fact, it wasn't even Einstein.

63
00:02:32,850 --> 00:02:36,540
I should give more credit
to Minkowski in 1907.

64
00:02:36,540 --> 00:02:38,340
So Einstein in 1905 figured out

65
00:02:38,340 --> 00:02:41,520
that you could get rid of the ether,

66
00:02:41,520 --> 00:02:43,860
the idea of a rest frame for the universe,

67
00:02:43,860 --> 00:02:47,040
and all the equations of
physics would make sense

68
00:02:47,040 --> 00:02:49,980
with the speed of light being a maximum.

69
00:02:49,980 --> 00:02:51,420
But then it was Minkowski,

70
00:02:51,420 --> 00:02:53,760
who used to be Einstein's
professor in 1907,

71
00:02:53,760 --> 00:02:55,440
who realized the most elegant way

72
00:02:55,440 --> 00:03:00,090
of thinking about this idea of
Einstein's was to blend space

73
00:03:00,090 --> 00:03:02,670
and time together into spacetime

74
00:03:02,670 --> 00:03:05,940
to really imagine that there is no hard

75
00:03:05,940 --> 00:03:08,820
and fast division of the
four dimensional world

76
00:03:08,820 --> 00:03:11,880
in which we live into
space and time separately.

77
00:03:11,880 --> 00:03:15,180
Einstein was at first dismissive of this.

78
00:03:15,180 --> 00:03:16,013
He thought it was just like,

79
00:03:16,013 --> 00:03:19,080
oh, the mathematicians
are overformalizing again.

80
00:03:19,080 --> 00:03:23,970
But then he later realized
that if spacetime is a thing,

81
00:03:23,970 --> 00:03:25,650
it can have properties

82
00:03:25,650 --> 00:03:27,480
and in particular it can have a geometry.

83
00:03:27,480 --> 00:03:29,580
It can be curved from place to place.

84
00:03:29,580 --> 00:03:32,400
And that was what let him
solve the problem of gravity.

85
00:03:32,400 --> 00:03:36,690
He had previously been
trying to fit in what we knew

86
00:03:36,690 --> 00:03:39,840
about gravity from Newtonian mechanics,

87
00:03:39,840 --> 00:03:42,030
the inverse square law of gravity

88
00:03:42,030 --> 00:03:43,710
to his new relativistic theory.

89
00:03:43,710 --> 00:03:44,880
It didn't work.

90
00:03:44,880 --> 00:03:46,920
So the final leap was to say,

91
00:03:46,920 --> 00:03:50,310
gravity is the curvature of spacetime.

92
00:03:50,310 --> 00:03:53,010
And that statement is
basically general relativity.

93
00:03:53,010 --> 00:03:56,760
- And the tension with Minkowski
was he was a mathematician.

94
00:03:56,760 --> 00:03:57,666
- [Sean] Yes.

95
00:03:57,666 --> 00:03:59,430
- So it's the tension between
physics and mathematics.

96
00:03:59,430 --> 00:04:02,400
In fact, in your lecture
about this equation,

97
00:04:02,400 --> 00:04:04,050
one of them,

98
00:04:04,050 --> 00:04:08,160
you say that Einstein
is a better physicist

99
00:04:08,160 --> 00:04:09,690
than he gets credit for.

100
00:04:09,690 --> 00:04:10,523
- Yep.

101
00:04:10,523 --> 00:04:11,910
(Sean laughs)

102
00:04:11,910 --> 00:04:12,743
- I know that's hard.

103
00:04:12,743 --> 00:04:14,436
That's a little bit of
a joke there, right?

104
00:04:14,436 --> 00:04:15,269
- [Lex] Yeah.

105
00:04:15,269 --> 00:04:17,160
- Because we all give
Einstein a lot of credit.

106
00:04:17,160 --> 00:04:20,790
But then we also, partly based on fact

107
00:04:20,790 --> 00:04:22,860
but partly to make ourselves feel better,

108
00:04:22,860 --> 00:04:24,090
tell ourselves a story about

109
00:04:24,090 --> 00:04:27,600
how later in life
Einstein couldn't keep up.

110
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:29,580
There were younger people
doing quantum mechanics

111
00:04:29,580 --> 00:04:31,320
and quantum field theory
and particle physics,

112
00:04:31,320 --> 00:04:33,270
and he was just sort of unable

113
00:04:33,270 --> 00:04:36,960
to really philosophically get
over his objections to that.

114
00:04:36,960 --> 00:04:39,120
And I think that that story

115
00:04:39,120 --> 00:04:41,520
about the latter part is completely wrong,

116
00:04:41,520 --> 00:04:43,380
like almost 180 degrees wrong.

117
00:04:43,380 --> 00:04:46,920
I think that Einstein
understood quantum mechanics

118
00:04:46,920 --> 00:04:48,600
as well as anyone,

119
00:04:48,600 --> 00:04:50,520
at least up through the 1930s.

120
00:04:50,520 --> 00:04:53,820
I think that his philosophical
objections to it are correct.

121
00:04:53,820 --> 00:04:56,340
So he should actually
have been taken much more

122
00:04:56,340 --> 00:04:58,050
seriously about that.

123
00:04:58,050 --> 00:04:59,820
And what he did,

124
00:04:59,820 --> 00:05:01,680
what he achieved in trying

125
00:05:01,680 --> 00:05:03,510
to think these problems through,

126
00:05:03,510 --> 00:05:06,180
is to really basically understand the idea

127
00:05:06,180 --> 00:05:07,740
of quantum entanglement,

128
00:05:07,740 --> 00:05:10,290
which is kind of important
these days when it comes

129
00:05:10,290 --> 00:05:12,240
to understanding quantum mechanics.

130
00:05:12,240 --> 00:05:15,210
Now, it's true that in
the forties and fifties,

131
00:05:15,210 --> 00:05:18,330
he placed his efforts in hopes

132
00:05:18,330 --> 00:05:20,910
for unifying electricity
and magnetism with gravity.

133
00:05:20,910 --> 00:05:23,310
That didn't really work out very well.

134
00:05:23,310 --> 00:05:26,010
All of us try things that don't work out.

135
00:05:26,010 --> 00:05:27,150
I don't hold that against him.

136
00:05:27,150 --> 00:05:29,070
But in terms of IQ points,

137
00:05:29,070 --> 00:05:31,560
in terms of trying to be a
clear thinking physicist,

138
00:05:31,560 --> 00:05:33,300
he was really, really great.

139
00:05:33,300 --> 00:05:35,700
- What does greatness
look like for a physicist?

140
00:05:35,700 --> 00:05:37,690
So how difficult is it

141
00:05:38,760 --> 00:05:40,550
to take the leap from special relativity

142
00:05:40,550 --> 00:05:42,300
to general relativity?

143
00:05:42,300 --> 00:05:44,500
How difficult is it to imagine that

144
00:05:45,840 --> 00:05:48,390
to consider spacetime together

145
00:05:48,390 --> 00:05:52,143
and to imagine that there's a
curvature to this whole thing?

146
00:05:53,220 --> 00:05:55,230
- Yeah, that's a great question.

147
00:05:55,230 --> 00:05:56,250
I think that if you want

148
00:05:56,250 --> 00:05:58,080
to make the case Einstein's greatness,

149
00:05:58,080 --> 00:05:59,700
which is not hard to do,

150
00:05:59,700 --> 00:06:00,810
there's two things you point at.

151
00:06:00,810 --> 00:06:03,270
One is in 1905,

152
00:06:03,270 --> 00:06:05,880
his famous miracle year,

153
00:06:05,880 --> 00:06:09,390
he writes three different papers

154
00:06:09,390 --> 00:06:11,700
on three wildly different subjects,

155
00:06:11,700 --> 00:06:15,090
all of which would make you famous

156
00:06:15,090 --> 00:06:16,690
just for writing that one paper.

157
00:06:17,580 --> 00:06:20,100
Special relativity is one of them.

158
00:06:20,100 --> 00:06:22,080
Brownian motion is another one,

159
00:06:22,080 --> 00:06:24,120
which is just the little vibrations

160
00:06:24,120 --> 00:06:26,520
of tiny little dust specs in the air.

161
00:06:26,520 --> 00:06:27,690
But who cares about that?

162
00:06:27,690 --> 00:06:30,330
What matters is it proves
the existence of atoms.

163
00:06:30,330 --> 00:06:31,980
He explains Brownian motion

164
00:06:31,980 --> 00:06:33,540
by imagining there are
molecules in the air

165
00:06:33,540 --> 00:06:34,740
and deriving their properties.

166
00:06:34,740 --> 00:06:35,760
Brilliant.

167
00:06:35,760 --> 00:06:38,670
And then he basically starts the world

168
00:06:38,670 --> 00:06:41,610
on the road to quantum
mechanics with his paper on...

169
00:06:41,610 --> 00:06:43,890
Which, again, is given a boring label

170
00:06:43,890 --> 00:06:45,780
of the photoelectric effect.

171
00:06:45,780 --> 00:06:48,570
What it really was is he invented photons.

172
00:06:48,570 --> 00:06:51,390
He showed that light should
be thought of as particles,

173
00:06:51,390 --> 00:06:52,860
as well as waves.

174
00:06:52,860 --> 00:06:54,960
And he did all three of
those very different things

175
00:06:54,960 --> 00:06:55,793
in one year.

176
00:06:55,793 --> 00:06:56,626
Okay.

177
00:06:56,626 --> 00:06:59,190
But the other thing that
gets him genius status is,

178
00:06:59,190 --> 00:07:01,470
like you say, general relativity.

179
00:07:01,470 --> 00:07:04,290
So this takes 10 years from 1905 to 1915.

180
00:07:04,290 --> 00:07:05,850
He wasn't only doing general relativity.

181
00:07:05,850 --> 00:07:06,683
He was working on other things.

182
00:07:06,683 --> 00:07:07,516
He wrote...

183
00:07:07,516 --> 00:07:09,180
He invented refrigerator.

184
00:07:09,180 --> 00:07:11,610
He did various interesting things.

185
00:07:11,610 --> 00:07:13,710
and he wasn't even the only
one working on the problem.

186
00:07:13,710 --> 00:07:14,580
There were other people

187
00:07:14,580 --> 00:07:17,880
who suggested relativistic
theories of gravity,

188
00:07:17,880 --> 00:07:21,300
but he really applied himself to it.

189
00:07:21,300 --> 00:07:25,080
And I think as your question suggests,

190
00:07:25,080 --> 00:07:29,430
the solution was not a
matter of turning a crank.

191
00:07:29,430 --> 00:07:32,553
It was something fundamentally creative.

192
00:07:33,390 --> 00:07:35,880
In his own telling of the story,

193
00:07:35,880 --> 00:07:37,530
his greatest moment,

194
00:07:37,530 --> 00:07:39,450
his happiest moment was when he realized

195
00:07:39,450 --> 00:07:42,990
that if the way that we would
modern, say, in modern terms,

196
00:07:42,990 --> 00:07:46,950
if you were in a rocket
ship accelerating at 1 g

197
00:07:46,950 --> 00:07:49,440
at one acceleration due to gravity,

198
00:07:49,440 --> 00:07:50,820
if the rocket ship were very quiet,

199
00:07:50,820 --> 00:07:52,470
you wouldn't be able
to know the difference

200
00:07:52,470 --> 00:07:53,790
between being in a rocket ship

201
00:07:53,790 --> 00:07:55,680
and being on the surface of the earth.

202
00:07:55,680 --> 00:07:59,190
Gravity is sort of not detectable

203
00:07:59,190 --> 00:08:02,190
or at least not distinguishable
from acceleration.

204
00:08:02,190 --> 00:08:03,023
So number one,

205
00:08:03,023 --> 00:08:04,800
that's a pretty clever thing to think.

206
00:08:04,800 --> 00:08:05,633
But number two,

207
00:08:05,633 --> 00:08:06,510
if you or I had that thought,

208
00:08:06,510 --> 00:08:07,343
we would've gone, "Huh?

209
00:08:07,343 --> 00:08:08,490
We're pretty clever."

210
00:08:08,490 --> 00:08:12,000
Heath reasons from there to say,

211
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:14,880
okay, if gravity is not detectable,

212
00:08:14,880 --> 00:08:17,910
then it can't be like an ordinary force.

213
00:08:17,910 --> 00:08:19,530
The electromagnetic force is detectable.

214
00:08:19,530 --> 00:08:21,600
We can put charge particles around.

215
00:08:21,600 --> 00:08:22,920
Positively charged particles

216
00:08:22,920 --> 00:08:25,860
and negatively charged
particles respond differently

217
00:08:25,860 --> 00:08:28,320
to an electric field
or to a magnetic field.

218
00:08:28,320 --> 00:08:31,140
He realizes that what his
thought experiment showed,

219
00:08:31,140 --> 00:08:32,190
or at least suggested,

220
00:08:32,190 --> 00:08:33,780
is that gravity isn't like that.

221
00:08:33,780 --> 00:08:37,590
Everything responds in
the same way to gravity.

222
00:08:37,590 --> 00:08:39,330
How could that be the case?

223
00:08:39,330 --> 00:08:41,250
And then this other leap he makes is, oh,

224
00:08:41,250 --> 00:08:43,440
it's 'cause it's the
curvature of spacetime.

225
00:08:43,440 --> 00:08:44,970
It's a feature of spacetime.

226
00:08:44,970 --> 00:08:47,550
It's not a force on top of it.

227
00:08:47,550 --> 00:08:49,230
And the feature that it is, is curvature.

228
00:08:49,230 --> 00:08:50,070
And then finally,

229
00:08:50,070 --> 00:08:51,570
he says, "Okay.

230
00:08:51,570 --> 00:08:55,350
Clearly, I'm gonna need the
mathematical tools necessary

231
00:08:55,350 --> 00:08:57,270
to describe curvature.

232
00:08:57,270 --> 00:08:58,800
I don't know them,

233
00:08:58,800 --> 00:08:59,970
so I will learn them."

234
00:08:59,970 --> 00:09:04,110
And they didn't have MOOCs or
AI helpers back in those days.

235
00:09:04,110 --> 00:09:06,270
He had to sit down and
read the math papers,

236
00:09:06,270 --> 00:09:08,430
and he taught himself
differential geometry

237
00:09:08,430 --> 00:09:09,840
and invented general relativity.

238
00:09:09,840 --> 00:09:12,120
- What about the step of including time

239
00:09:12,120 --> 00:09:13,860
as just another dimension?

240
00:09:13,860 --> 00:09:16,070
So combining space and time.

241
00:09:16,070 --> 00:09:21,070
Is that a simple mathematical
leap as Minkowski suggested?

242
00:09:21,210 --> 00:09:24,180
- It's certainly not simple, actually.

243
00:09:24,180 --> 00:09:25,691
It's a profound insight.

244
00:09:25,691 --> 00:09:28,120
That's why I said I think we should give

245
00:09:28,980 --> 00:09:31,170
Minkowski more credit than we do.

246
00:09:31,170 --> 00:09:33,480
He's the one who really
put the finishing touches

247
00:09:33,480 --> 00:09:35,250
on special relativity.

248
00:09:35,250 --> 00:09:38,040
Again, many people had talked about

249
00:09:38,040 --> 00:09:42,540
how things change when you move
close to the speed of light,

250
00:09:42,540 --> 00:09:44,010
what Maxwell's equations

251
00:09:44,010 --> 00:09:46,440
of electromagnetism predict and so forth,

252
00:09:46,440 --> 00:09:47,430
what their symmetries are.

253
00:09:47,430 --> 00:09:50,250
So people like Lorentz, and
FitzGerald, and Lorentz,

254
00:09:50,250 --> 00:09:52,170
there's a story that goes there

255
00:09:52,170 --> 00:09:54,330
and in the usual telling Einstein sort

256
00:09:54,330 --> 00:09:56,100
of puts the capstone on it.

257
00:09:56,100 --> 00:09:59,340
He's the one who says all of
this makes much more sense.

258
00:09:59,340 --> 00:10:00,840
If there just is no ether,

259
00:10:00,840 --> 00:10:01,950
it is undetectable.

260
00:10:01,950 --> 00:10:04,170
We don't know how fast
everything is relative,

261
00:10:04,170 --> 00:10:05,850
thus, the name relativity.

262
00:10:05,850 --> 00:10:08,520
But he didn't take the actual final step,

263
00:10:08,520 --> 00:10:11,340
which was to realize that
the underlying structure

264
00:10:11,340 --> 00:10:14,520
that he had invented is best thought of

265
00:10:14,520 --> 00:10:16,590
as unifying space and time together.

266
00:10:16,590 --> 00:10:18,090
I honestly don't know what was going

267
00:10:18,090 --> 00:10:21,390
through Minkowski's mind
when he thought that.

