the data and the human data

2618
01:39:06,720 --> 01:39:09,870
and the vast landscape of human data

2619
01:39:09,870 --> 01:39:12,180
that AI models, large language models,

2620
01:39:12,180 --> 01:39:15,783
and video models in the
future are trained on,

2621
01:39:17,070 --> 01:39:20,190
don't you think that that
intentionality will emerge

2622
01:39:20,190 --> 01:39:24,720
as fundamental to the behavior
of these systems naturally?

2623
01:39:24,720 --> 01:39:26,250
- Well, I don't think it
will happen naturally.

2624
01:39:26,250 --> 01:39:27,750
I think it could happen again.

2625
01:39:27,750 --> 01:39:30,630
I'm not against the principle.

2626
01:39:30,630 --> 01:39:35,630
But, again, the way that large
language models came to be

2627
01:39:36,420 --> 01:39:40,200
and what they're optimized
for is wildly different

2628
01:39:40,200 --> 01:39:41,457
than the way that human beings came to be

2629
01:39:41,457 --> 01:39:43,740
and what they're optimized for.

2630
01:39:43,740 --> 01:39:48,540
So I think we're missing a chance

2631
01:39:48,540 --> 01:39:50,640
to be much more clearheaded

2632
01:39:50,640 --> 01:39:53,100
about what large language models are

2633
01:39:53,100 --> 01:39:54,840
by judging them against human beings,

2634
01:39:54,840 --> 01:39:57,030
again, both in positive
ways and negative ways.

2635
01:39:57,030 --> 01:39:58,650
- Well, I think it sort of to push back

2636
01:39:58,650 --> 01:40:00,990
on what they're optimized
for is different to describe

2637
01:40:00,990 --> 01:40:03,750
how they're trained versus
what they're optimized for.

2638
01:40:03,750 --> 01:40:05,940
So they're trained is very trivial way

2639
01:40:05,940 --> 01:40:07,533
of predicting text tokens,

2640
01:40:08,550 --> 01:40:10,560
but you can describe what
they're optimized for

2641
01:40:10,560 --> 01:40:12,930
and what the actual task in hand is,

2642
01:40:12,930 --> 01:40:15,210
is to construct a world model,

2643
01:40:15,210 --> 01:40:17,310
meaning an understanding of the world.

2644
01:40:17,310 --> 01:40:19,770
And that's where it starts getting closer

2645
01:40:19,770 --> 01:40:21,870
to what humans are kind of doing,

2646
01:40:21,870 --> 01:40:24,570
or just in the case of
large language models,

2647
01:40:24,570 --> 01:40:25,770
know how the sausage is made

2648
01:40:25,770 --> 01:40:28,470
and we don't know how
it's made for us humans.

2649
01:40:28,470 --> 01:40:29,760
- But they're not optimized for that.

2650
01:40:29,760 --> 01:40:31,230
They're optimized to sound human.

2651
01:40:31,230 --> 01:40:32,790
- That's the fine-tuning.

2652
01:40:32,790 --> 01:40:37,263
But the actual training is
optimized for understanding,

2653
01:40:38,188 --> 01:40:41,760
creating a compressed representation

2654
01:40:41,760 --> 01:40:44,520
of all the stuff that humans
have created on the internet.

2655
01:40:44,520 --> 01:40:46,770
And the hope is that

2656
01:40:46,770 --> 01:40:50,160
that gives you a deep
understanding of the world.

2657
01:40:50,160 --> 01:40:50,993
- Yeah.

2658
01:40:50,993 --> 01:40:52,650
So that's why I think that there's a set

2659
01:40:52,650 --> 01:40:54,060
of interesting questions

2660
01:40:54,060 --> 01:40:56,580
to be asked about the ways

2661
01:40:56,580 --> 01:40:58,140
in which large language models

2662
01:40:58,140 --> 01:41:00,780
actually do represent the world

2663
01:41:00,780 --> 01:41:02,490
because what is clear is

2664
01:41:02,490 --> 01:41:05,043
that they're very good at acting human.

2665
01:41:05,940 --> 01:41:08,640
The open question in my mind is,

2666
01:41:08,640 --> 01:41:10,560
is the easiest, most efficient,

2667
01:41:10,560 --> 01:41:13,860
best way to act human
to do the same things

2668
01:41:13,860 --> 01:41:15,240
that human beings do?

2669
01:41:15,240 --> 01:41:16,920
Or are there other ways?

2670
01:41:16,920 --> 01:41:18,930
And I think that's an open question.

2671
01:41:18,930 --> 01:41:20,700
I just heard a talk by Melanie Mitchell

2672
01:41:20,700 --> 01:41:21,810
at Santa Fe Institute,

2673
01:41:21,810 --> 01:41:24,090
an artificial intelligence researcher.

2674
01:41:24,090 --> 01:41:26,820
And she told two stories
about two different papers.

2675
01:41:26,820 --> 01:41:27,810
One that someone else wrote

2676
01:41:27,810 --> 01:41:29,850
and one that her group is following up on.

2677
01:41:29,850 --> 01:41:31,920
And they were modeling Othello.

2678
01:41:31,920 --> 01:41:34,380
Othello the game with a
little rectangular board,

2679
01:41:34,380 --> 01:41:35,580
white and black squares.

2680
01:41:35,580 --> 01:41:37,620
So the experiment was the following.

2681
01:41:37,620 --> 01:41:40,680
They fed a neural network,

2682
01:41:40,680 --> 01:41:45,270
the moves that were being made
in the most symbolic form.

2683
01:41:45,270 --> 01:41:47,190
Like E5 just means that, okay,

2684
01:41:47,190 --> 01:41:48,750
you put a token down E5,

2685
01:41:48,750 --> 01:41:50,100
so it gives a long string.

2686
01:41:50,100 --> 01:41:51,930
It does this for millions of games,

2687
01:41:51,930 --> 01:41:53,700
real legitimate games.

2688
01:41:53,700 --> 01:41:54,960
And then it asks the question,

2689
01:41:54,960 --> 01:41:56,160
the paper asks the question,

2690
01:41:56,160 --> 01:41:58,380
okay, you you've trained it

2691
01:41:58,380 --> 01:42:01,710
to tell what would be
a legitimate next move

2692
01:42:01,710 --> 01:42:03,543
from not a legitimate next move.

2693
01:42:05,070 --> 01:42:06,900
Did it in its brain

2694
01:42:06,900 --> 01:42:07,943
and it's a little large
language model brain.

2695
01:42:07,943 --> 01:42:09,090
I don't even know

2696
01:42:09,090 --> 01:42:10,380
if it's technically a
large language model,

2697
01:42:10,380 --> 01:42:12,150
but a deep learning network.

2698
01:42:12,150 --> 01:42:15,840
Did it come up with a
representation of the Othello board?

2699
01:42:15,840 --> 01:42:16,710
Well, how do you know?

2700
01:42:16,710 --> 01:42:19,410
And so they construct
a little probe network

2701
01:42:19,410 --> 01:42:20,400
that they insert

2702
01:42:20,400 --> 01:42:23,200
and ask it what is it doing
right at this moment, right?

2703
01:42:24,939 --> 01:42:28,440
The little probe network can ask,

2704
01:42:28,440 --> 01:42:29,580
would this be legitimate

2705
01:42:29,580 --> 01:42:32,640
or is this token white
or black or whatever?

2706
01:42:32,640 --> 01:42:36,150
Things that in practice would amount to...

2707
01:42:36,150 --> 01:42:39,060
It's invented the Othello board.

2708
01:42:39,060 --> 01:42:43,140
And it found that the
probe got the right answer,

2709
01:42:43,140 --> 01:42:44,790
not a hundred percent of the time,

2710
01:42:44,790 --> 01:42:46,440
but more than by chance,

2711
01:42:46,440 --> 01:42:48,603
substantially more than by chance.

2712
01:42:49,590 --> 01:42:52,560
So they said there's
some tentative evidence

2713
01:42:52,560 --> 01:42:56,340
that this neural network has
discovered the Othello board

2714
01:42:56,340 --> 01:42:58,113
just out of data, raw data.

2715
01:42:59,220 --> 01:43:01,470
But then Melanie's group
asked the question,

2716
01:43:01,470 --> 01:43:05,106
okay, are you sure that that understanding

2717
01:43:05,106 --> 01:43:08,583
of the Othello board wasn't
built into your probe?

2718
01:43:10,170 --> 01:43:11,850
And what they found was like at least half

2719
01:43:11,850 --> 01:43:13,980
of the improvement was
built into the probe.

2720
01:43:13,980 --> 01:43:14,883
Not all of it.

2721
01:43:15,990 --> 01:43:20,643
And look, a Othello board is
way simpler than the world.

2722
01:43:24,090 --> 01:43:26,400
I just think it's an open question,

2723
01:43:26,400 --> 01:43:28,740
whether or not the...

2724
01:43:28,740 --> 01:43:31,290
I mean, it would be remarkable either way

2725
01:43:31,290 --> 01:43:33,600
to learn that large language models

2726
01:43:33,600 --> 01:43:37,350
that are good at doing what
we train them to do are good

2727
01:43:37,350 --> 01:43:39,840
because they've built the same
kind of model of the world

2728
01:43:39,840 --> 01:43:41,490
that we have in our minds,

2729
01:43:41,490 --> 01:43:44,820
or that they're good despite
not having that model.

2730
01:43:44,820 --> 01:43:46,470
Either one of these is an amazing thing.

2731
01:43:46,470 --> 01:43:49,110
I just don't think the data
are clear on which one is true.

2732
01:43:49,110 --> 01:43:51,030
- I think I have some sort

2733
01:43:51,030 --> 01:43:52,860
of intellectual humility
about the whole thing

2734
01:43:52,860 --> 01:43:55,740
because I was humbled by several stages

2735
01:43:55,740 --> 01:43:58,983
in the machine learning
development over the past 20 years.

2736
01:44:00,690 --> 01:44:03,520
And I was just would never have predicted

2737
01:44:04,380 --> 01:44:08,100
that LLMs the way they're trained

2738
01:44:08,100 --> 01:44:10,710
on the scale of data they're
trained would be as impressive

2739
01:44:10,710 --> 01:44:11,700
as they are.

2740
01:44:11,700 --> 01:44:14,440
And there, that's where
intellectual humility steps in

2741
01:44:15,300 --> 01:44:18,180
where my intuition would say
something like with Melanie,

2742
01:44:18,180 --> 01:44:21,180
where you need to be
able to have very sort

2743
01:44:21,180 --> 01:44:23,280
of concrete common sense reasoning,

2744
01:44:23,280 --> 01:44:26,880
symbolic reasoning type things in a system

2745
01:44:26,880 --> 01:44:30,180
in order for it to be very intelligent.

2746
01:44:30,180 --> 01:44:34,560
But here, I'm so impressed
by what it's capable to do,

2747
01:44:34,560 --> 01:44:37,263
train on the next token
prediction essentially.

2748
01:44:38,970 --> 01:44:42,600
My conception of the nature

2749
01:44:42,600 --> 01:44:45,210
of intelligence is just completely,

2750
01:44:45,210 --> 01:44:48,630
not completely but humbled, I should say.

2751
01:44:48,630 --> 01:44:49,980
- Look, and I think that's perfectly fair.

2752
01:44:49,980 --> 01:44:54,120
I also was, I will say pleasantly,

2753
01:44:54,120 --> 01:44:55,590
but I don't know whether it's
pleasantly or unpleasantly,

2754
01:44:55,590 --> 01:44:58,830
but factually surprised by
the recent rate of progress.

2755
01:44:58,830 --> 01:44:59,880
Clearly, some kind

2756
01:44:59,880 --> 01:45:02,880
of phase transition
percolation has happened

2757
01:45:02,880 --> 01:45:04,710
and the improvement has been remarkable.

2758
01:45:04,710 --> 01:45:06,240
Absolutely amazing,

2759
01:45:06,240 --> 01:45:09,570
that I have no arguments with.

2760
01:45:09,570 --> 01:45:13,740
That doesn't yet tell me the mechanism

2761
01:45:13,740 --> 01:45:16,350
by which that improvement happened.

2762
01:45:16,350 --> 01:45:17,520
Constructing a model,

2763
01:45:17,520 --> 01:45:19,710
much like a human being
would have is clearly

2764
01:45:19,710 --> 01:45:21,090
one possible mechanism,

2765
01:45:21,090 --> 01:45:22,770
but part of the intellectual humility is

2766
01:45:22,770 --> 01:45:24,930
to say maybe there are others.

2767
01:45:24,930 --> 01:45:25,815
- I was chatting with the CEO
of Anthropic, Dario Amodei,

2768
01:45:25,815 --> 01:45:30,815
so behind (indistinct) and that company.

2769
01:45:32,490 --> 01:45:35,760
But a lot of the AI
companies are really focused

2770
01:45:35,760 --> 01:45:38,160
on expanding the scale of compute,

2771
01:45:38,160 --> 01:45:42,990
sort of if we assume that
AI is not data-limited

2772
01:45:42,990 --> 01:45:44,793
but is compute-limited,

2773
01:45:46,470 --> 01:45:48,360
you can make the system
much more intelligence

2774
01:45:48,360 --> 01:45:49,983
by using more compute.

2775
01:45:51,210 --> 01:45:55,920
So let me ask you on almost
on the physics level.

2776
01:45:55,920 --> 01:45:59,460
Do you think physics can help
expand the scale of compute

2777
01:45:59,460 --> 01:46:01,290
and maybe the scale of energy required

2778
01:46:01,290 --> 01:46:02,760
to make that compute happen?

2779
01:46:02,760 --> 01:46:03,593
- Yeah, a hundred percent.

2780
01:46:03,593 --> 01:46:04,560
I think this is like one

2781
01:46:04,560 --> 01:46:08,280
of the biggest things that
physics can help with.

2782
01:46:08,280 --> 01:46:11,610
And it's an obvious kind of
low-hanging fruit situation

2783
01:46:11,610 --> 01:46:16,610
where the heat generation,
the inefficiency,

2784
01:46:17,580 --> 01:46:22,580
the waste of existing
high level computers is

2785
01:46:23,400 --> 01:46:26,250
nowhere near the efficiency of our brains.

2786
01:46:26,250 --> 01:46:27,810
It's hilariously worse.

2787
01:46:27,810 --> 01:46:29,550
And we kind of haven't tried to optimize

2788
01:46:29,550 --> 01:46:30,900
that hard on that frontier.

2789
01:46:30,900 --> 01:46:32,220
I mean, your laptop heats up

2790
01:46:32,220 --> 01:46:33,810
when you're sitting on your lap, right?

2791
01:46:33,810 --> 01:46:34,643
It doesn't need to.

2792
01:46:34,643 --> 01:46:36,260
Your brain doesn't heat up like that.

2793
01:46:37,320 --> 01:46:40,350
So, clearly, there exists
in the world of physics,

2794
01:46:40,350 --> 01:46:43,260
the capability of doing these computations

2795
01:46:43,260 --> 01:46:45,930
with much less waste heat being generated.

2796
01:46:45,930 --> 01:46:48,090
And I look forward to people doing that.

2797
01:46:48,090 --> 01:46:48,923
Yeah.

2798
01:46:48,923 --> 01:46:51,290
- Are you excited for the
possibility of a nuclear fusion?

2799
01:46:52,200 --> 01:46:53,820
- I am cautiously optimistic.

2800
01:46:53,820 --> 01:46:55,200
Excited it'll be too strong.

2801
01:46:55,200 --> 01:46:56,313
I mean, it'd be great.

2802
01:46:57,270 --> 01:46:59,790
But if we really tried solar power,

2803
01:46:59,790 --> 01:47:01,150
it would also be great.

2804
01:47:01,150 --> 01:47:02,010
(Lex laughs)

2805
01:47:02,010 --> 01:47:04,020
- I think Ilya Sutskever said this,

2806
01:47:04,020 --> 01:47:06,780
that the future of humanity

2807
01:47:06,780 --> 01:47:09,750
on earth will be just, the entire surface

2808
01:47:09,750 --> 01:47:12,990
of earth is covered in solar
panels and data centers.

2809
01:47:12,990 --> 01:47:14,160
- Why would you waste the surface of the

2810
01:47:14,160 --> 01:47:15,180
earth with solar panels?

2811
01:47:15,180 --> 01:47:16,140
Put them in space.

2812
01:47:16,140 --> 01:47:17,550
- Sure, you can go in space.

2813
01:47:17,550 --> 01:47:18,383
Yeah.

2814
01:47:18,383 --> 01:47:20,070
- Space is bigger than the earth.

2815
01:47:20,070 --> 01:47:20,903
- Yeah.

2816
01:47:20,903 --> 01:47:21,736
Just solar panels everywhere.

2817
01:47:21,736 --> 01:47:22,569
- [Sean] Yeah.

2818
01:47:23,670 --> 01:47:24,503
I like it.

2819
01:47:24,503 --> 01:47:25,830
- We already have fusion.

2820
01:47:25,830 --> 01:47:26,910
It's called the sun.

2821
01:47:26,910 --> 01:47:28,617
- [Lex] Yeah, that's true.

2822
01:47:28,617 --> 01:47:31,380
And there's probably more
and more efficient ways

2823
01:47:31,380 --> 01:47:33,180
of catching that energy.

2824
01:47:33,180 --> 01:47:35,460
- Sending it down is the
hard part, absolutely.

2825
01:47:35,460 --> 01:47:37,350
But that's an engineering problem.

2826
01:47:37,350 --> 01:47:38,183
Yeah.

2827
01:47:38,183 --> 01:47:41,370
- So I just wonder where the data centers,

2828
01:47:41,370 --> 01:47:43,740
the compute centers can expand to.

2829
01:47:43,740 --> 01:47:44,670
If that's the future,

2830
01:47:44,670 --> 01:47:49,200
if AI is as effective
as it possibly could be,

2831
01:47:49,200 --> 01:47:53,370
then it's the scale of
computation will keep increasing,

2832
01:47:53,370 --> 01:47:56,790
but perhaps it's a race
between efficiency and scale.

2833
01:47:56,790 --> 01:47:57,750
- There are constraints.

2834
01:47:57,750 --> 01:47:58,583
- [Lex] Yeah.

2835
01:47:58,583 --> 01:47:59,788
- There's a certain amount of energy,

2836
01:47:59,788 --> 01:48:01,410
a certain amount of damage
we can do to the environment

2837
01:48:01,410 --> 01:48:03,390
before it does not worth it anymore.

2838
01:48:03,390 --> 01:48:05,640
So, yeah, I think that's a new question.

2839
01:48:05,640 --> 01:48:07,260
In fact, it's kind of frustrating

2840
01:48:07,260 --> 01:48:09,540
because we get better and better

2841
01:48:09,540 --> 01:48:11,190
at doing things efficiently,

2842
01:48:11,190 --> 01:48:13,683
but we invent more
things we wanna do faster

2843
01:48:13,683 --> 01:48:16,200
than we get good at
doing them efficiently.

2844
01:48:16,200 --> 01:48:19,830
So we're continuing to make
things worse in various ways.

2845
01:48:19,830 --> 01:48:21,858
- I mean, that's the dance of humanity.

2846
01:48:21,858 --> 01:48:24,047
We're constantly creating better, better,

2847
01:48:24,047 --> 01:48:26,370
better technologies that
are potentially causing

2848
01:48:26,370 --> 01:48:27,930
a lot more harm.

2849
01:48:27,930 --> 01:48:29,310
And that includes for weapons.

2850
01:48:29,310 --> 01:48:31,110
It includes AI used as weapons.

2851
01:48:31,110 --> 01:48:33,090
That includes nuclear weapons, of course.

2852
01:48:33,090 --> 01:48:35,010
Which is surprising to me

2853
01:48:35,010 --> 01:48:38,610
that we haven't destroyed
human civilization yet

2854
01:48:38,610 --> 01:48:41,550
given how many nuclear
warheads are out there.

2855
01:48:41,550 --> 01:48:42,510
- Look, I'm with you.

2856
01:48:42,510 --> 01:48:45,990
Between nuclear and bio weapons,

2857
01:48:45,990 --> 01:48:47,250
it is a little bit surprising

2858
01:48:47,250 --> 01:48:49,440
that we haven't caused
enormous devastation.

2859
01:48:49,440 --> 01:48:51,690
Of course, we did drop
two atomic bombs on Japan,

2860
01:48:51,690 --> 01:48:53,490
but compared to what could have happened

2861
01:48:53,490 --> 01:48:55,083
or could happen tomorrow,

2862
01:48:56,250 --> 01:48:57,270
it could be much worse.

2863
01:48:57,270 --> 01:48:58,103
- Yeah.

2864
01:48:58,103 --> 01:49:00,030
It does seem like there's a underlying,

2865
01:49:00,030 --> 01:49:01,980
speaking of quantum fields,

2866
01:49:01,980 --> 01:49:04,470
there's like a field

2867
01:49:04,470 --> 01:49:08,310
of goodness within the human heart

2868
01:49:08,310 --> 01:49:11,310
that like in some kind
of game theoretic way,

2869
01:49:11,310 --> 01:49:12,870
we create really powerful things

2870
01:49:12,870 --> 01:49:13,980
that could destroy each other.

2871
01:49:13,980 --> 01:49:15,240
And there's greed and ego

2872
01:49:15,240 --> 01:49:18,510
and all this kind power hungry dictators

2873
01:49:18,510 --> 01:49:22,440
that are at play here in all
the geopolitical landscape,

